author: Rajulapudi Srinivas
title: Rain and clogged drains leave many roads waterlogged in Vijayawada - The Hindu
text:
Several roads were inundated and many areas saw power cuts as rainfall accompanied by thunderstorms and gales lashed the city on May 10 (Friday), causing inconvenience to the citizens.
Pedestrians were seen wading through knee-deep water on the roads in Moghalrajpuram, Benz Circle, Sanathnagar, M.G. Road and other areas.
‚ÄúRain water was flowing on the roads in streets and on the National Highway as the garbage was not cleared from the drains. Many junctions in the city saw traffic snarls,‚Äù said S. Hanumantha Rao, a two-wheeler rider.
P. Srikanth, an employee of a laboratory, said he got stuck at Moghalrajpuram. He urged the Vijayawada Municipal Corporation (VMC) officials to clean the clogged drains which was preventing free flow of water.
Meanwhile, Andhra Pradesh State Disaster Management Authority (APSDMA) has cautioned that more rains are likely to occur in some districts in the next 48 hours.
APSDMA Managing Director Ronanki Kurmanath said that under the influence of a cyclonic circulation, light to moderate rain, accompanied by thunderstorms, is likely to occur in Eluru, Krishna, Guntur, East Godavari, Kakinada, Anakapalli, ASR, Srikakulam, Vizianagaram, West Godavari and Parvathipuram Manyam districts.
Light rainfall may occur in Tirupati, Chittoor, Annamayya, Kurnool and Ananthapuram district, Mr. Kurmanath said.
Farmers, agriculture labourers and cattle rearers have been advised not to stay under trees and in open places during the thunderstorms, he added.

author: Allison Quinn
title: Spanish Priest Don Alfonso Sidelined by Church for Allegedly Hawking Viagra
text: A Spanish priest has been sidelined by the Roman Catholic Church after he was busted by the Civil Guard‚Äôs organized-crime unit for allegedly selling Viagra and other ‚Äúaphrodisiac substances‚Äù out of his home. Identified in local reports as a long-time parish priest from the small town of Don Benito, he is now receiving ‚Äúpsychological and spiritual‚Äù help during his temporary suspension, the diocese of Plasencia announced in a statement on Thursday, adding that it was ‚Äúdismayed‚Äù by the ‚Äúscandal‚Äù swirling around the case. Known as Don Alfonso, the priest was detained Monday but later provisionally released, while a second man who was arrested‚Äîdescribed in local reports as Don Alfonso‚Äôs boyfriend‚Äîhas remained in custody. According to El Mundo , Don Alfonso was monitored by the Civil Guard‚Äôs Organized-Crime and Anti-Drug Unit for months before cops finally swooped in and arrested him. Authorities claim he and the second man had been receiving deliveries of Viagra from other European countries and then selling it out of a rented apartment in Don Benito. Jes√∫s Carretero, a lawyer for the priest, has disputed the allegations, telling the newspaper that Don Alfonso had ‚Äúno knowledge‚Äù of any drug trafficking and ‚Äúthere is no evidence that incriminates him.‚Äù
